Blacken00100 wrote:hawkbox wrote:What makes you think that special exceptions can't be made for people that with usWhat makes me think that? Hmm. How about, "everything you've said in this thread?"You are IT. That makes you a support component of the organization. You are not the lords and masters of all you nmap. You support production staff. Production staff says "we need this," you say "OK" unless it is actively dangerous to other business goals (and "we don't want to use a database" isn't a business goal)."The users" that you sneer at are more important than you are. You are there to support them. What makes things "easier to manage" is of less importance than making the users optimally effective (and that often means "making them happy," which is something you write like it's a curse).Quote:f you act like the entitled prick you seem to be there definitely wouldn't be an exception for you.You calling anyone "entitled" is really, really funny. Let's turn that one around: "people have to come beg and scrape for an exception to name their own computers, and if we don't like their attitude we'll just say no!" That's entitlement--that you deserve to be part of the process when you aren't a value-add.There's a reason that "IT" and "red tape" are so stereotypically synonymous. You're demonstrating it.Fine. Here's your machine, named "HURR_DUUR" or whatever the fuck you want. It's now YOURS - it breaks, you fix it. It won't connect to the corporate LAN - wupps, better figure it out yerself, Mr. "But-IT-is-a-cost-centre-I-MAKE-Money!" developer, because our automated scripts just won't be able to process that name, without a lot of development effort to accomodate one special princess and that adds cost and complexity without a gain for the buisines as a whole. We don't have time to take care of one special snowflake, when we've got a snowdrift to shepperd in the right direction.It's about give and take - if you want it all, you get it all. Now go play with *your* machine while we in "IT" make things work for everyone else, at minimal cost to the company, with the best experience possible for our users.Oh, and because you "know computers" through past experience, does not make you an honourary admin. It's our pool and we say who plays in it, because our jobs and professional reputation are kind of important to us. You are in userland - if you don't have any professional skin in the game, feel free to troll, rant or do whatever else you need to do to vent you impotent anger, I just don't care. HAND.(Appologies - thread moved faster that I was typing - I'll shut up now. )
