Noodle wrote:There should be an application called "Support Information" and a huge honking button (etc)In the 'old' system, that very app was my baby.In the 'new' system, I threw the old code at someone who developed a specific app for the new system, which is in the 'quickstart' tray of every workstation:It has tabs to say what the workstation is, what apps are installed, and what local and Active Directory groups the user has membership to. (split infinitives, yay).It's an insanely useful tool.With regards to the IT Vs User-Space war in the thread (Blacken et al), it's easy to see where both sides are coming from.Unfortunately for Blacken (who I love dearly, because of the Minecraft clone he's working on), he's wrong.Not because he can't do what he does with 'corporate' IT equipment, but because his 'I yam more productive if I do shit my own way' attitude CANNOT work in a larger organisation.Believe me, I know.When you're dealing with tens of thousands of desktops, you have a Standard Operating Environment (SOE) for corporate IT (email, applications, etc). If a developer wants a playground machine, fine, let them have it, but don't call that machine/environment an SOE, and don't expect Corporate IT Support for your special sandbox, because they ain't geared for it.I can visualise the thrashing of gears "but, I WORK in a way that works best for ME and Information Technology just want to put blockers in my way", on one side, and the 'if Special Snowflake is on MY books, his computer will follow MY rules!'They are incompatible viewpoints.IT can be relaxed, mixed, crazy funtime with amazing output from enthusiastic employees, but that all goes out the window for -corporate- stuff, where SOE is the only sane way to go, and 'development' environments are sandboxed, safe from actual 'production' environments, and vice versa.Of course, it's dependent upon the context. In a 50 person company, such attitudes as Blackened expresses are 'normal'. In a 5,000 person company, not as much, and in a 15,000+ person company, no fucking way.I hope that makes sense on both sides of the fence, as I hope my butchered PNG comes through the vagaries of Ars' current pictar processing process.
