Major General Thanatos wrote:Huzzah for users that think before clicking!I know, a rare treat!Best story I have on that was when I worked for a company that had a HUGE database. Like 10s of millions of customer records. One day, one of the billing reps got a popup, "you need administrative privileges to process that request." This was on a simple query. So she asked her supervisor who looked at the popup, closed it out, and re-logged in as the rep to reproduce the error. Simple query, same popup. She smelled a rat, and called the dev team for the database.Long story short, turns out, some 6 months earlier, a DBA had been fired. Apparently, for the years he worked there, he had a "time bomb" in the code which he updated with each push. Hidden deep in some section was a piece of code that went something like, "If after [date], delete all master keys." That needed administrative privileges. Had the billing admin logged in as administrator, even a simple query would have wiped out the database's master keys, rendering it useless. Backups would have also been wiped as they were installed until someone discovered the code in the client front end.I don't recall now what happened to the former employee, but I believe he was brought up on charges. The billing admin got a small award plaque and a bonus for her diligence, and the billing rep got some free lunch.
