Posted: Sun Jun 10, 2012 9:01 am
The best timebomb I'm aware of didn't harm the live data, it damaged the backups and prevented accurate reporting and recovery. It did nothing to the live database, but it encrypted information from the data warehouse if a request was made through the front-end (publicly accessible) website for a specific record (doing so, though, only after reports were run, so it looked like everything was ok).Turns out, someone decided to hammer the website looking for script vulnerabilities and discovered that one of the urls passed a value. They just scanned through while incrementing that value looking for unexpected behavior. In so doing, they found the secret url and kicked off the bomb.A few months later, the guy (who still worked there) was in a meeting when someone mentioned that there were problems with the data warehouse. He looked and realized what had happened. Unfortunately, since he didn't kick off the bomb from the remote site, he had no clue what value had been used to encrypt the data. He quit before they tracked the code back to him.
