hux wrote:Wouldn't have helped in this situation. From the description, the time bomb was dead man's switch, reset with each code update, that the guy set up long before he ever got fired.Yep. In fact, IIRC, he was the writer of the front end for the most part, and no one cross-checked his code until they found a backup of the code repository or something. Where I work now, a former admin, when faced with an unstable system, had put in some code that simply restarted the service if it failed to respond in a set amount of time. Fear of his shitty fix being discovered, he made it a hidden file in /etc/cron.d/ which later bit us in the ass when we set up a replacement system, and turned off the service on the old one. At some point, the old server (which was still on for another reason) just relaunched the service quietly and started to compete with the new server behind a virtual IP. Hilarity did not ensue. Part of the nefarious nature of his service is that it did not announce it had restarted (as per protocol; all restarts, stops, starts. and reloads must be documented), so we had no idea for 24 hours until we accidentally assumed someone else turned on the service, shut it off, only to have it quietly turn back on again.That and hard-coded IPs. I could fucking kill someone who does this in code.
