Happysin wrote:Quote:That and hard-coded IPs. I could fucking kill someone who does this in code.No doubt. My old company had a serious issue with one of their clients. The client had some devices made overseas that were supposed to communicate with a specific website and transmit data. The overseas manufacturer was also responsible for all code that would be on the device. they built those devices to only look for one IP address. Not the actual website name, its IP address.Suffice to say, they didn't catch that until the devices were already manufactured and shipped, so about a year later, we had to help them triage a way to get a firmware update to all those devices (which were, due to the nature of what they were doing, in rather remote location), because their host couldn't handle them anymore, and wasn't being helpful about the IP address they had.Sounds very similar to something that happened to me, was this in the MRO supply industry?
